---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="ostk security — signed, verified, audited"
     description="ostk security model: GPG-signed binaries, dual-signature trust, audit trail for every edit. Proof-backed.">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Security</h1>

    <p class="lead">Every write is signed. Every identity is verified. Every conflict is resolved — never silently.</p>

    <h2>Trust tiers</h2>
    <p>Identity in ostk is determined by the <strong>GPG web of trust</strong> — not by platform accounts. Your trust tier is resolved at boot from cross-signatures in your keyring.</p>

    <img src="/diagrams/trust-tiers.svg" alt="Trust tier capability matrix showing T0 through T3 permissions for read, write, governance, and agent operations" class="diagram" />

    <table class="trust-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Tier</th>
          <th>What it means</th>
          <th>How you get it</th>
          <th>Default restrictions</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="tier tier-0">T0</span></td>
          <td>Dual-signed (human + kernel)</td>
          <td>Ratified by an existing T0 holder</td>
          <td>None — full governance</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="tier tier-1">T1</span></td>
          <td>Cross-signed by T0 holder</td>
          <td>Your GPG key signed by a T0 key</td>
          <td>Cannot modify OS or governance files</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="tier tier-2">T2</span></td>
          <td>GPG on GitHub, not cross-signed</td>
          <td>GitHub account with verified GPG key</td>
          <td>Read-only — cannot modify OS, governance, or source</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="tier tier-3">T3</span></td>
          <td>Anonymous</td>
          <td>No GPG key</td>
          <td>Cannot boot — public artifacts only</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p class="note">GitHub is used for identity discovery — where you find a key fingerprint. The authority is the cross-signature chain, not the platform.</p>

    <img src="/diagrams/web-of-trust.svg" alt="GPG web of trust: T0 root and human keys cross-sign T1 kernel and CI keys, T2 escalates via cross-signing, T3 anonymous" class="diagram" />

    <h3>Escalation</h3>
    <p>Trust escalates through GPG cross-signing, not through platform permissions:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>T3 → T2:</strong> Generate a GPG key and add it to your GitHub account.</li>
      <li><strong>T2 → T1:</strong> Get your key cross-signed by a T0 holder. Share your fingerprint; they sign your key with <code>gpg --sign-key</code>.</li>
      <li><strong>T1 → T0:</strong> Dual-signed ratification — requires both a human and the kernel to attest.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>The write path</h2>
    <p>Every file edit routes through the kernel. Five checks, in order:</p>

    <img src="/diagrams/write-path.svg" alt="The write path: pin check, CAS check, exclusive flock, gen_table attribution, shadow + audit" class="diagram" />

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Pin check</strong> — does your trust tier allow this write? If the path is denied by your tier-default pin, the write is silently blocked. The agent never knows.</li>
      <li><strong>CAS check</strong> — does the content match what you think it does? If not, the write fails before it starts.</li>
      <li><strong>Exclusive flock</strong> — one writer at a time per file. No concurrent writes overwrite each other silently.</li>
      <li><strong>gen_table attribution</strong> — every write records who wrote it, when, and from which agent alias.</li>
      <li><strong>Hot PR resolution</strong> — overlapping edits get assisted merge. Never a silent overwrite.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Each write produces a gen_table entry:</p>
    <pre><code>{`{"path":"src/main.rs","generation":42,"writer":"agent-934","timestamp":"2026-03-11T09:14:32Z","mtime":1741684472}`}</code></pre>

    <p>The gen counter is monotonically increasing per file. Gaps in the sequence are visible — there is no way to edit a file without leaving a record.</p>

    <h2>Capability pins</h2>
    <p>Pins are invisible capability boundaries enforced at the write path. Your trust tier determines your default restrictions at boot — no configuration needed.</p>

    <table class="trust-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Tier</th>
          <th>Default pin</th>
          <th>Effect</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="tier tier-0">T0</span></td>
          <td>None</td>
          <td>Full access — governance, OS, source</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="tier tier-1">T1</span></td>
          <td><code>deny: write-kernel modify-governance</code></td>
          <td>Can write source. Cannot touch OS state or governance files.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="tier tier-2">T2</span></td>
          <td><code>deny: write-kernel modify-governance write-src</code></td>
          <td>Read-only in practice. Can boot, explore, run benchmarks.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="tier tier-3">T3</span></td>
          <td>Cannot boot</td>
          <td>Public artifacts only — releases, documentation.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>Explicit pins (via <code>ostk run --pin</code>) can only <strong>add</strong> restrictions on top of your tier default. The tier is a floor, not an override. A T2 user cannot escape <code>write-src</code> denial through a custom pin.</p>

    <p>When an agent writes to a denied path, the write is silently blocked. The agent never knows. The audit trail records it. This is by design — the OS is invisible to the agents running on it.</p>
    <p>Every release binary is signed by the CI key before it is published. Verify before you run:</p>

    <pre><code># Replace the version with the one you downloaded
$ gpg --verify ostk-v2.3.0-aarch64-apple-darwin.tar.gz.asc
gpg: Good signature from "ostk.ai (the kernel survives) &lt;contact@ostk.ai&gt;"
gpg: using EDDSA key 5FF41DFFB92A22E1EAD68E0B69FD844FE1B53386</code></pre>

    <p>The CI signing key is ed25519, cross-signed by the root key, and expires 2028. The CI key can be revoked without touching the root. Revoked keys are published immediately.</p>

    <h2>Bail verification</h2>
    <p>A bail is a portable snapshot of OS state — used to hand off a session to another instance. Every bail is verifiable:</p>

    <pre><code>$ ostk bail verify team.bail
✓ manifest signed
✓ signer: &lt;fingerprint&gt;
✓ contents: boot.md + .boot/INIT + .primefile
✓ no internal state exposed</code></pre>

    <p>A public bail contains no secrets, no audit logs, no session data. Only what another instance needs to boot. The manifest signature proves the bail was not tampered with in transit.</p>

    <h2>Proof</h2>
    <p>Every claim on this page is backed by a passing test. The bench suite runs in Docker on every release. Pass/fail. No partial credit.</p>

    <table class="proof-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Test file</th><th>What it proves</th><th>Tests</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><a href="https://github.com/os-tack/ostk.ai/blob/main/tests/bench_auth_chain.rs"><code>bench_auth_chain.rs</code></a></td>
          <td>Trust tier assignment (T2 default, T1 requires verified identity), HUMANFILE secrets gate, harness_identity parsing, authority chain invariants</td>
          <td>16</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><a href="https://github.com/os-tack/ostk.ai/blob/main/tests/bench_write_path_unprotected.rs"><code>bench_write_path_unprotected.rs</code></a></td>
          <td>Concurrent-write stress: flock exclusion, CAS correctness under contention, no silent overwrites</td>
          <td>5</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><a href="https://github.com/os-tack/ostk.ai/blob/main/tests/bench_kernel_active.rs"><code>bench_kernel_active.rs</code></a></td>
          <td>Kernel presence: active write path, audit trail completeness, gen counter monotonicity</td>
          <td>5</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p><a href="/bench">View full bench results →</a></p>

    <h2>Threat model</h2>
    <p>Security review conducted 2026-03-11. Scope: identity, secrets, file CAS, run pipeline. 10 findings filed. 8 fixed, 2 mitigated, 0 open.</p>

    <table class="findings-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>ID</th><th>Severity</th><th>Surface</th><th>Status</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>FIND-001</td><td><span class="sev p0">P0</span></td><td>identity.rs — unsigned harness_identity allows T1 spoofing</td><td><span class="status-fixed">fixed</span> — →619: boot.md ownership check, SUDO_UID handling, T2 fallback</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FIND-002</td><td><span class="sev p0">P0</span></td><td>secret.rs — HAYSTACK_SECRET_CMD exec without validation</td><td><span class="status-fixed">fixed</span> — →620: reads from .ostk/config, not env var</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FIND-003</td><td><span class="sev p1">P1</span></td><td>secret.rs — run_env() prints secrets to stdout</td><td><span class="status-mitigated">mitigated</span> — warns user, recommends --env-passthrough. Intentional for <code>secret env</code> subcommand</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FIND-004</td><td><span class="sev p1">P1</span></td><td>run.rs — env-passthrough key name injection</td><td><span class="status-fixed">fixed</span> — HUMANFILE SECRET authorization required; absent key → denied</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FIND-005</td><td><span class="sev p1">P1</span></td><td>run.rs — HUMANFILE absent not fail-closed</td><td><span class="status-fixed">fixed</span> — missing HUMANFILE returns empty map → no keys authorized</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FIND-006</td><td><span class="sev p1">P1</span></td><td>file.rs — str_replace_all() missing flock</td><td><span class="status-fixed">fixed</span> — lock_exclusive() before read-modify-write cycle</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FIND-007</td><td><span class="sev p2">P2</span></td><td>identity.rs — alias reclaim race</td><td><span class="status-mitigated">mitigated</span> — scoped to process death; low practical risk</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FIND-008</td><td><span class="sev p2">P2</span></td><td>identity.rs — stale harness_identity reuse</td><td><span class="status-fixed">fixed</span> — →895: GPG web-of-trust replaced harness_identity as trust source</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FIND-009</td><td><span class="sev p2">P2</span></td><td>parser.rs — PROMPT file:// path traversal</td><td><span class="status-fixed">fixed</span> — canonicalize + starts_with check; traversal returns denial string, not file content</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FIND-010</td><td><span class="sev p3">P3</span></td><td>audit.jsonl — no append-only enforcement at OS level</td><td><span class="status-fixed">fixed</span> — truncation detection via size checkpoint under flock; external truncation refuses write</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>Full mitigations: <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/ostk.ai/blob/main/docs/security/threat-model.md">docs/security/threat-model.md</a></p>

    <h2>Source availability</h2>
    <p>The ostk kernel is closed-source. You cannot audit the implementation of write interception, conflict resolution, or capability enforcement by reading source code. The security claims on this page are verified through the test harness linked above, the published threat model, and GPG-signed release binaries. If source auditability is a requirement for your threat model, this is a constraint you should weigh.</p>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .lead {
    font-size: var(--ostk-text-md);
    color: var(--ostk-text-primary);
    line-height: var(--ostk-leading-relaxed);
    margin-bottom: var(--ostk-space-8);
  }

  .trust-table {
    margin-top: var(--ostk-space-4);
  }

  .tier {
    font-family: var(--ostk-font-mono);
    font-size: var(--ostk-text-xs);
    font-weight: var(--ostk-weight-bold);
    padding: 0.2em 0.5em;
    border-radius: var(--ostk-radius-sm);
    letter-spacing: var(--ostk-tracking-wide);
  }

  .tier-0 {
    background: rgba(212, 160, 84, 0.15);
    color: var(--ostk-needle-bright);
    border: 1px solid rgba(212, 160, 84, 0.3);
  }

  .tier-1 {
    background: rgba(90, 154, 106, 0.12);
    color: var(--ostk-ok);
    border: 1px solid rgba(90, 154, 106, 0.25);
  }

  .tier-2 {
    background: rgba(90, 138, 180, 0.12);
    color: var(--ostk-info);
    border: 1px solid rgba(90, 138, 180, 0.25);
  }

  .tier-3 {
    background: var(--ostk-bg-raised);
    color: var(--ostk-text-muted);
    border: 1px solid var(--ostk-border-subtle);
  }

  .note {
    font-size: var(--ostk-text-sm);
    color: var(--ostk-text-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    margin-top: calc(-1 * var(--ostk-space-2));
  }

  h2 { margin-top: var(--ostk-space-12); }
  h2:first-of-type { margin-top: var(--ostk-space-8); }

  .proof-table, .findings-table {
    width: 100%;
    margin-top: var(--ostk-space-4);
    font-size: var(--ostk-text-sm);
  }

  .findings-table td:first-child {
    font-family: var(--ostk-font-mono);
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  .sev {
    font-family: var(--ostk-font-mono);
    font-size: var(--ostk-text-xs);
    font-weight: var(--ostk-weight-bold);
    padding: 0.15em 0.4em;
    border-radius: var(--ostk-radius-sm);
  }

  .sev.p0 { background: rgba(220,80,80,0.15); color: #e05050; border: 1px solid rgba(220,80,80,0.3); }
  .sev.p1 { background: rgba(212,160,84,0.15); color: var(--ostk-needle-bright); border: 1px solid rgba(212,160,84,0.3); }
  .sev.p2 { background: rgba(90,138,180,0.12); color: var(--ostk-info); border: 1px solid rgba(90,138,180,0.25); }
  .sev.p3 { background: var(--ostk-bg-raised); color: var(--ostk-text-muted); border: 1px solid var(--ostk-border-subtle); }

  .status-fixed {
    font-family: var(--ostk-font-mono);
    font-size: var(--ostk-text-xs);
    font-weight: var(--ostk-weight-bold);
    color: var(--ostk-ok);
    background: rgba(90, 154, 106, 0.12);
    padding: 0.15em 0.4em;
    border-radius: var(--ostk-radius-sm);
    border: 1px solid rgba(90, 154, 106, 0.25);
  }

  .status-mitigated {
    font-family: var(--ostk-font-mono);
    font-size: var(--ostk-text-xs);
    font-weight: var(--ostk-weight-bold);
    color: var(--ostk-needle-bright);
    background: rgba(212, 160, 84, 0.12);
    padding: 0.15em 0.4em;
    border-radius: var(--ostk-radius-sm);
    border: 1px solid rgba(212, 160, 84, 0.25);
  }

  .status-open {
    font-family: var(--ostk-font-mono);
    font-size: var(--ostk-text-xs);
    font-weight: var(--ostk-weight-bold);
    color: #e05050;
    background: rgba(220, 80, 80, 0.12);
    padding: 0.15em 0.4em;
    border-radius: var(--ostk-radius-sm);
    border: 1px solid rgba(220, 80, 80, 0.25);
  }
</style>
